  "prompt": "Can a constitutional amendment be deemed unconstitutional by the Supreme Court?",
  "response": "No, the Supreme Court cannot declare a constitutional amendment unconstitutional. This is because constitutional amendments are, by definition, part of the Constitution itself. Once an amendment is properly ratified according to the procedures outlined in Article V of the Constitution, it becomes a valid part of the supreme law of the land. \n\nThe Supreme Court's power of judicial review allows it to declare laws unconstitutional if they conflict with the Constitution, but amendments are considered to be part of the Constitution. Therefore, the Court cannot invalidate a properly ratified amendment.\n\nHowever, the Court can interpret the meaning and application of constitutional amendments, which can significantly impact how they are implemented in practice.",
